Evidence in page: 
Hertha Dorthea Elisabeth Sponer (1 September 1895 – 27 February 1968) was a German physicist and chemist who contributed to modern quantum mechanics and molecular physics. She was the first woman on the physics faculty of Duke University and was one of only three women to earn both a PhD in Physics and Habilitation in Germany before the start of World War II... She then enrolled at the University of Göttingen where she received her PhD in 1920 under the supervision of Peter Debye. Her dissertation was titled "Über ultrarote Absorption zweiatomiger Gase"... In October 1925 she received a Rockefeller Foundation fellowship to stay at University of California, Berkeley, where she remained for a year. During her time at Berkeley, she collaborated with R. T. Birge, developing what is now called the Birge-Sponer method for determining dissociation energies... in 1934 she was dismissed from her position when Hitler came to power, due to the Nazis' stigma against women in academia. In 1934 Sponer moved to Oslo to teach at the University of Oslo as a visiting professor, and in 1936 she started her appointment at Duke University where she remained as a professor until 1966 when she became professor emeritus... During her academic career, Sponer conducted research in quantum mechanics, physics, and chemistry. She authored and published numerous studies, many of which were in collaboration with famous physicists including Edward Teller.

Summary: 
Hertha Sponer (1895–1968) was a pioneering German physicist and chemist who made significant contributions to quantum mechanics and molecular physics. She received her PhD in 1920 from the University of Göttingen under Peter Debye. During a fellowship at UC Berkeley in 1925, she collaborated with R. T. Birge to develop the Birge-Sponer method for determining dissociation energies. Dismissed from her academic position in Germany due to the Nazi regime's discrimination against women in academia, she emigrated and eventually joined Duke University in 1936. She became the first woman on Duke's physics faculty, where she set up a spectroscopy lab, researched extensively, and taught until her retirement in 1966.
