Summary: 
Carver Andress Mead (born May 1, 1934) is a prominent American scientist, engineer, and the Gordon and Betty Moore Professor Emeritus of Engineering and Applied Science at Caltech, where he taught for over 40 years. A pioneer in modern microelectronics, he significantly contributed to the development of semiconductors, digital chips, silicon compilers, and very-large-scale integration (VLSI) chip design, notably coauthoring the classic 1980 textbook 'Introduction to VLSI Systems' with Lynn Conway. Later in his career, he explored neuromorphic electronic systems by modeling human neurology and has also called for a reconceptualization of modern physics. In addition to his academic work, he has been involved in founding over 20 companies. He is the recipient of numerous prestigious honors, including the National Medal of Technology (2002) and the Kyoto Prize (2022).
