Evidence in page: 
Born: Willy Otto Oskar Ley October 2, 1906 Berlin, German Empire.

Occupations: science writer and historian of science.

At the University of Berlin, he studied astronomy, physics, zoology, and paleontology.

He then became interested in spaceflight after reading Hermann Oberth's book Die Rakete zu den Planetenräumen (The Rocket into Interplanetary Space). ... Ley became one of the first members of Germany's amateur rocket group, the Verein für Raumschiffahrt (VfR – "Spaceflight Society") in 1927 and wrote extensively for its journal, Die Rakete (The Rocket).

Meanwhile, some rocket researchers formed closer ties with the military, which greatly expanded under the leadership of Wernher von Braun. With the collapse of the VfR, the rise of a culture of necessary secrecy and the loss of public enthusiasm, Ley grew discouraged... To make ends meet, Ley also worked as a clerk and then manager at a Berlin bank. When the Nazis seized power, Ley's situation became increasingly desperate... Ley fled Germany for the United Kingdom and ultimately the United States.

Ley was best known for his books on rocketry and related topics...

Categories: ... 20th-century American physicists ... 20th-century German physicists ... German aerospace engineers ... German rocket scientists

Summary: 
Willy Ley matches most of the provided clues but not all. He was born in the 1900s (October 2, 1906) in Berlin. He studied physics at the University of Berlin and is categorized as a 20th-century physicist. He was heavily involved in rocket science as an early member of Germany's Spaceflight Society and as a prolific author on rocketry and space travel. However, the text does not support the claim that he was a military flight engineer. Instead, he was primarily a science writer and actually distanced himself from rocketry when it became militarized under the Nazi regime, eventually fleeing Germany.
