Evidence in page: 
The Vavilov State Optical Institute in St Petersburg, Russia (named after Sergey Ivanovich Vavilov) is a research institute in optics in Russia.

It was established in 1918 along the lines of a proposal by the physicist Dimitri Rozhdestvensky, who was the first director, a post he held until 1932.

The leading role in this process was played by D. S. Rozhdestvensky, who at that time was the head of the Physics Institute of Petrograd University and at the same time chairman of the Department of Optometry of the Commission for the Study of the Natural Productive Forces of Russia (KEPS) at the Russian Academy of Sciences.

The Department of Optical Engineering arose in April 1918, and in May, at the initiative and request of Rozhdestvensky, a computing bureau and an experimental optical workshop were established under him. Later, D. S. Rozhdestvensky linked the formation of the institute with these events and said that the GOI "originated" in May 1918.

On December 15, 1918, the first organizational meeting of the Scientific Council of the GOI was held under the chairmanship of D. S. Rozhdestvensky.

Directors
Interim CEO - Bezborodkin Pavel Vladimirovich (from 2021)

Summary: 
Based on the webpage content, three prominent individuals are associated with the Vavilov State Optical Institute. First, Sergey Ivanovich Vavilov, whom the institute is named after. Second, the physicist Dimitri Rozhdestvensky (D. S. Rozhdestvensky), who proposed its establishment, played a critical role in its foundation in 1918, and served as its first director until 1932. Third, Pavel Vladimirovich Bezborodkin, who is listed as the Interim CEO starting from 2021. This information fully satisfies the user's goal of identifying people connected to the institute.
