Mikhail Mikhailovich Rusinov (Russian: Михаил Михайлович Русинов, 11 February 1909 – 29 September 2004) was a Russian scientist specialising in optics. He co-founded the USSR Science School of Computational Optics and discovered several optical phenomena, including aberration vignetting (1938), projection centre distortion (1957), and existence of second-order aberration (1986).

Rusinov was born into the family of a high school mathematics teacher. His father Mikhail Nikolayevich Rusinov taught at the N. A. Rimsky-Korsakov Saint Petersburg State Conservatory. His mother Yevdokiya Vasilyevna Rusinova studied piano under Anton Rubinstein. Mikhail Rusinov inherited his mother's love of music and composed waltzes as an adult.

Rusinov attended school from 1917 to 1920; in 1921 he entered a trade school that eventually became the Professional School of Precise Mechanics and Optics... After graduation from technical school at the age of 18, Rusinov joined the Leningrad Optical Mechanical Association (LOMO) as an optician designer.

Rusinov's scientific work is closely associated with ITMO University. He worked at ITMO from its foundation, holding the position of Department Head for more than 40 years... Rusinov wrote more than 152 scientific papers (18 monographs), and held 320 Inventor's Certificates and 22 patents (7 in Russia).

Rusnov was married to Nadezhda Agaltsova, a colleague who shared with him the 1982 Lenin Prize for the development of wide-angle aerophotography lenses. He was an accomplished piano player and music composer. He was also an avid winter swimmer... Awards and honors: Three Stalin Prizes (1941, 1949, 1950), Order of Lenin (1961), USSR State Prize (1967), Order of the Red Banner of Labour (1981), Lenin Prize (1982).

Summary: 
Mikhail Rusinov (1909–2004) was a prominent Russian optical scientist who co-founded the USSR Science School of Computational Optics. He is known for discovering optical phenomena such as aberration vignetting and projection centre distortion, and held numerous patents and inventor's certificates. His career was deeply connected to ITMO University and LOMO. He received significant recognition, including three Stalin Prizes, the Order of Lenin, and a Lenin Prize (shared with his wife and colleague, Nadezhda Agaltsova). Outside of science, Rusinov was an accomplished pianist, composer, and an avid winter swimmer. This comprehensive profile should provide the necessary details to cross-reference with any specific clues.
