Evidence in page: 
Dmitry Dmitrievich Maksutov (Russian: Дми́трий Дми́триевич Максу́тов; 23 April [O.S. 11 April] 1896 – 12 August 1964) was a Soviet optical engineer and amateur astronomer. He is best known as the inventor of the Maksutov telescope.

His grandfather, Dmitri Petrovich Maksutov, was the last Russian governor of Russian Alaska, before it was purchased by the United States in 1867.

Dmitri became interested in astronomy in early childhood, and constructed his first telescope (a 7.2 inch / 180 mm reflector) when he was twelve years old... At 15 years of age he had already been accepted as a member of the Russian Astronomical Society. Three years later he graduated from the Military Nikolayev Engineering Institute...

Maksutov's most well known contribution in the field of optics was made in 1941, when he invented the Maksutov telescope. Like the Schmidt telescope, the Maksutov corrects for spherical aberration by placing a corrector lens in front of the primary mirror... Maksutov's telescope uses a deeply curved full diameter negative meniscus lens (a "meniscus corrector shell").

He also created a photo-gastrograph (used for photographing the stomach), a needle-microscope, shadow instruments for aerodynamic tubes, telescopic spectacles, and other instruments.

Awards: Stalin Prize (1941, 1946), two Orders of Lenin (1945,1958), Order The Badge of Honour (1943), Grand Prix at the Expo '58 in Brussels

Summary: 
Dmitry Dmitrievich Maksutov (1896-1964) was a Soviet optical engineer and amateur astronomer, widely recognized for inventing the Maksutov telescope in 1941, which uniquely uses a meniscus corrector shell to correct spherical aberration. Born into a family with a strong naval history, his grandfather was the last Russian governor of Russian Alaska. A prodigy in optics, Maksutov built his first telescope at age 12 and joined the Russian Astronomical Society at 15. In addition to his namesake telescope, he invented the photo-gastrograph, needle-microscope, and various lenses and prisms. For his contributions to science, he received numerous accolades, including the Stalin Prize, Orders of Lenin, and the Grand Prix at the 1958 Brussels Expo. This detailed profile provides comprehensive clues about his life, family background, and scientific legacy to help verify any specific criteria.
