Summary: 
Aleksandr Alekseevich Lebedev (November 26, 1893 – March 15, 1969) was a prominent Russian and Soviet physicist. He specialized in applied and electron optics, atmospheric and hydrooptics, laser technology, and the physics of glass. Working primarily at the State Optical Institute (GOI) and Leningrad State University, he became an Academician of the USSR Academy of Sciences in 1943. For his extensive scientific contributions, he was awarded the title of Hero of Socialist Labor (1957), the Lenin Prize (1959), and two Stalin Prizes (1947, 1949).
